WEBVTT

00:06.089 --> 00:08.800
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:08.800 --> 00:12.179
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:12.179 --> 00:14.681
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:14.681 --> 00:16.225
<i>‐ My name is Tyler Hall.</i>

00:16.225 --> 00:17.726
I really fell in love

00:17.726 --> 00:20.062
with the endless amount
of things that you can do.

00:20.062 --> 00:21.355
<i>You can do the same</i>
<i>blade shape ten times</i>

00:21.355 --> 00:23.190
and it can be completely
different every time.

00:23.190 --> 00:24.525
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:24.525 --> 00:26.318
<i>‐ My name is Rocky Lemon.</i>

00:26.318 --> 00:27.861
Reason for bladesmithing,
you know,

00:27.861 --> 00:29.571
<i>it's just</i>
<i>a pressure release.</i>

00:29.571 --> 00:30.989
<i>Take all your aggressions out</i>

00:30.989 --> 00:33.158
<i>on a piece of steel</i>
<i>that doesn't really care.</i>

00:33.158 --> 00:34.368
Make a lot of fun with it.

00:34.368 --> 00:37.204
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:37.204 --> 00:39.373
‐ My name is Zane Burch.
I'm 19 years old.

00:39.373 --> 00:41.291
<i>When I was a kid,</i>
<i>I wanted to be a pirate,</i>

00:41.291 --> 00:43.335
<i>but that's not really</i>
<i>reasonable right now,</i>

00:43.335 --> 00:45.712
so bladesmithing was
the secondary alternative

00:45.712 --> 00:47.214
<i>for that.</i>
<i>[chuckles]</i>

00:47.214 --> 00:49.508
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:49.508 --> 00:51.051
<i>‐ My name's Chris Hedberg.</i>

00:51.051 --> 00:52.511
I'm really looking forward
to using Big Blue.

00:52.511 --> 00:54.304
<i>I think that might be</i>
<i>a common thing.</i>

00:54.304 --> 00:56.682
<i>Just to be able to hammer</i>
<i>on some hot steel</i>

00:56.682 --> 00:59.393
and see how it moves
underneath the hammer,

00:59.393 --> 01:01.395
I'm looking forward
to trying that out.

01:01.395 --> 01:03.105
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:03.105 --> 01:05.732
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:05.732 --> 01:07.943
You are here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:07.943 --> 01:09.736
of edged weapon‐making
competition

01:09.736 --> 01:12.531
specifically designed
to test every aspect

01:12.531 --> 01:14.074
of your bladesmithing
capabilities

01:14.074 --> 01:15.951
in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:15.951 --> 01:18.829
who tells me who's gotta go
and who wins the show,

01:18.829 --> 01:20.455
so let's meet your judges now.

01:20.455 --> 01:23.625
Up first, ABS Mastersmith
J. Neilson.

01:23.625 --> 01:25.460
Next, historic weapons
re‐creation specialist

01:25.460 --> 01:26.753
David Baker.

01:26.753 --> 01:30.299
And last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:30.299 --> 01:31.508
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:31.508 --> 01:34.386
Bladesmiths,
the weather's been changing,

01:34.386 --> 01:36.430
and in the spring,
we do spring cleaning,

01:36.430 --> 01:38.432
so in your first round
of competition,

01:38.432 --> 01:40.434
we found these laying around
The Forge for you guys to use.

01:40.434 --> 01:42.603
<i>[tense percussive music]</i>

01:42.603 --> 01:47.190
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:47.190 --> 01:48.900
<i>‐ I see this table of springs</i>

01:48.900 --> 01:52.279
and my brain just goes "poof."
[chuckles]

01:52.279 --> 01:55.073
‐ We found some springs
for you guys to use

01:55.073 --> 01:57.617
to make signature blades
in your signature style,

01:57.617 --> 01:59.119
and those blades must fall

01:59.119 --> 02:00.996
within the following
parameters.

02:00.996 --> 02:04.207
First of all, you must use
at least three different types

02:04.207 --> 02:07.377
of 5160 spring steel.

02:07.377 --> 02:09.463
The length of your blades
from tip to plunge grind

02:09.463 --> 02:12.049
must be
between 14 and 16 inches.

02:12.049 --> 02:13.508
<i>The overall length</i>
<i>of your blade</i>

02:13.508 --> 02:15.385
<i>must not exceed 22 inches.</i>

02:15.385 --> 02:18.013
And an acid etch
by the end of this round.

02:18.013 --> 02:20.390
Now, in the second round,
if you make it that far,

02:20.390 --> 02:22.392
you'll have a chance
to put handles on your blades

02:22.392 --> 02:24.853
so that we can test
their strength and durability

02:24.853 --> 02:27.606
in an oil can stab‐and‐chop

02:27.606 --> 02:31.735
and edge retention in
a leather vest stab‐and‐slice.

02:31.735 --> 02:33.320
When the time runs out

02:33.320 --> 02:35.030
and the judges
have inspected your work,

02:35.030 --> 02:36.823
one of you will have
to surrender your blade

02:36.823 --> 02:38.158
and leave The Forge.

02:38.158 --> 02:40.911
Good luck.
Your three hours starts...now.

02:40.911 --> 02:43.664
<i>[rock music]</i>

02:43.664 --> 02:46.541
All of our bladesmiths
trying to consolidate

02:46.541 --> 02:53.048
three different size springs
into one 14‐ to 16‐inch blade.

02:53.048 --> 02:54.716
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:54.716 --> 02:56.093
<i>‐ So this is gonna be simple.</i>

02:56.093 --> 02:59.221
All I gotta do is cut up
my springs, forge out a blade

02:59.221 --> 03:01.765
<i>larger than any</i>
<i>that I've ever forged before,</i>

03:01.765 --> 03:02.849
and then win!

03:02.849 --> 03:04.017
It's pretty easy.

03:04.017 --> 03:05.435
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:05.435 --> 03:07.437
I decided to try
canister Damascus.

03:07.437 --> 03:09.481
<i>‐ I'd definitely</i>
<i>go for the canister</i>

03:09.481 --> 03:11.191
so you can use the whole can

03:11.191 --> 03:13.235
and have some sacrificial steel
on the ends,

03:13.235 --> 03:15.904
or you can cut the can down
so it heats up quicker

03:15.904 --> 03:17.531
and you've got less metal
to work.

03:17.531 --> 03:19.950
<i>‐ Some people use white‐out</i>
<i>to create kind of a wall</i>

03:19.950 --> 03:23.453
<i>between the canister</i>
<i>and the inside materials,</i>

03:23.453 --> 03:26.081
<i>but I decided to try using</i>
<i>a different method.</i>

03:26.081 --> 03:29.167
‐ Zane has actually heated up
his can right away,

03:29.167 --> 03:31.169
which seems weird because
isn't there gonna be

03:31.169 --> 03:33.547
forge scale all inside
of that can?

03:33.547 --> 03:34.756
‐ Yep.

03:34.756 --> 03:36.091
<i>‐ I just let it oxidize</i>
<i>a little bit</i>

03:36.091 --> 03:38.385
<i>and kind of form a layer</i>
<i>on the inside,</i>

03:38.385 --> 03:40.303
and hopefully that will keep
the insides

03:40.303 --> 03:42.055
from sticking to the canister.

03:42.055 --> 03:43.390
‐ What do you think of that?

03:43.390 --> 03:44.433
‐ I think you just
leave the can on.

03:44.433 --> 03:46.268
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:46.268 --> 03:47.394
‐ I'm happy with springs.

03:47.394 --> 03:48.937
I don't have to tear
anything apart.

03:48.937 --> 03:50.230
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:50.230 --> 03:51.690
<i>I'm going with the three</i>
<i>smaller springs</i>

03:51.690 --> 03:54.025
<i>because there's less mess</i>
<i>with them,</i>

03:54.025 --> 03:56.111
easier to fit in the can.

03:56.111 --> 04:00.240
It's important to be working
efficiently, keep it simple.

04:00.240 --> 04:01.575
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:01.575 --> 04:04.703
<i>Once I get the springs</i>
<i>cut down to size,</i>

04:04.703 --> 04:08.248
I throw them in the can,
packing it full of 1095 powder.

04:08.248 --> 04:11.001
‐ We've got Chris
at the welding station.

04:11.001 --> 04:13.253
He will be the first
of our smiths

04:13.253 --> 04:15.922
to be welded up
and into the fire.

04:15.922 --> 04:19.050
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:19.050 --> 04:20.635
<i>‐ The whole reason</i>
<i>I'm on "Forged in Fire,"</i>

04:20.635 --> 04:22.345
<i>I really wanted</i>
<i>a hard challenge,</i>

04:22.345 --> 04:24.306
and this one, I think,
will take the cake.

04:24.306 --> 04:25.599
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:25.599 --> 04:28.143
<i>I decided to take the canister</i>

04:28.143 --> 04:31.605
and I'm gonna forge weld
one of the bigger springs

04:31.605 --> 04:33.940
<i>to the side</i>
<i>so that my cutting edge</i>

04:33.940 --> 04:35.942
will be solid steel.

04:35.942 --> 04:37.778
<i>Once I've got the canister</i>
<i>thrown in the fire,</i>

04:37.778 --> 04:40.030
<i>I'll start working on my coil</i>
<i>and get those two</i>

04:40.030 --> 04:41.782
to where I can get them
to an equal size.

04:41.782 --> 04:43.867
‐ When Tyler
put his can together,

04:43.867 --> 04:46.703
he only put two different size
springs in it; we need three.

04:46.703 --> 04:48.872
And he's gonna San Mai it
somehow to try to get

04:48.872 --> 04:50.749
that third size spring
in there.

04:50.749 --> 04:53.668
Tyler kind of made
twice as much work for himself.

04:53.668 --> 04:56.379
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:56.379 --> 04:59.633
<i>‐ I made several knives out</i>
<i>of old car springs and stuff.</i>

04:59.633 --> 05:01.343
I don't think it's gonna be
all that crazy.

05:01.343 --> 05:02.344
A knife's a knife.

05:02.344 --> 05:03.678
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:03.678 --> 05:05.472
<i>I'm gonna take</i>
<i>the largest spring,</i>

05:05.472 --> 05:07.557
<i>cut into three sections,</i>
<i>straighten them all out,</i>

05:07.557 --> 05:09.768
<i>clean them up,</i>
<i>take the other two springs‐‐</i>

05:09.768 --> 05:11.686
<i>smaller springs‐‐and wrap them</i>
<i>around each other,</i>

05:11.686 --> 05:13.104
<i>and forge weld</i>
<i>them all together</i>

05:13.104 --> 05:14.981
<i>around the main billet.</i>

05:14.981 --> 05:16.983
‐ I think Rocky's
going old‐school.

05:16.983 --> 05:19.402
Rocky's just gonna hammer
a bunch of stuff together,

05:19.402 --> 05:21.404
wrap it in wire.

05:21.404 --> 05:23.323
<i>‐ The risk is it don't weld,</i>

05:23.323 --> 05:24.741
<i>but it's all</i>
<i>the same material.</i>

05:24.741 --> 05:26.326
It should be a piece of cake.

05:26.326 --> 05:28.328
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:28.328 --> 05:30.121
‐ Two hours, bladesmiths!

05:30.121 --> 05:32.165
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:32.165 --> 05:33.500
‐ I got my weld set
on the press.

05:33.500 --> 05:35.335
<i>Now I'm ready</i>
<i>to draw my can out</i>

05:35.335 --> 05:36.545
into more of a billet shape.

05:36.545 --> 05:38.880
<i>I decide to leave</i>
<i>my canister on</i>

05:38.880 --> 05:40.924
<i>and hope that the forge scale</i>
<i>that I built up earlier</i>

05:40.924 --> 05:42.926
is not a interference.

05:42.926 --> 05:44.094
<i>I'm gonna be making a bowie</i>

05:44.094 --> 05:45.929
because that's kind of
my classic style.

05:45.929 --> 05:48.181
<i>It's a stab‐and‐chop</i>
<i>style weapon,</i>

05:48.181 --> 05:50.851
<i>and hopefully it'll</i>
<i>hold up well during the tests.</i>

05:50.851 --> 05:52.644
All right.

05:52.644 --> 05:53.937
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:53.937 --> 05:56.022
‐ Once I start pressing
my canister,

05:56.022 --> 05:58.358
<i>I know things are welding</i>

05:58.358 --> 06:01.111
<i>because once it starts</i>
<i>consolidating,</i>

06:01.111 --> 06:03.363
it almost hardens up.

06:03.363 --> 06:07.033
‐ Now, Chris actually
took his canister to Big Blue.

06:07.033 --> 06:10.161
‐ My concern is, he went
one pass on the press

06:10.161 --> 06:11.538
and then to the hammer,

06:11.538 --> 06:13.790
and we've seen that cause
cracking in billets before.

06:13.790 --> 06:15.876
‐ Hot metal!

06:15.876 --> 06:18.253
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:18.253 --> 06:21.882
‐ I've got this big old chunk
of spring here

06:21.882 --> 06:24.217
<i>that I've gotta</i>
<i>get hammered out flat.</i>

06:24.217 --> 06:27.596
<i>‐ Tyler still has to weld</i>
<i>that piece onto the canister.</i>

06:27.596 --> 06:29.097
<i>He's got that can and he's got</i>

06:29.097 --> 06:30.932
<i>that piece</i>
<i>he's working on now.</i>

06:30.932 --> 06:34.394
<i>Those have to become</i>
<i>one piece of steel.</i>

06:34.394 --> 06:36.938
‐ I'm planning on making
a pretty traditional

06:36.938 --> 06:38.732
<i>Japanese tanto‐style blade.</i>

06:38.732 --> 06:40.150
<i>I know that we're gonna be</i>
<i>doing some stabbing,</i>

06:40.150 --> 06:41.526
<i>we're gonna be doing</i>
<i>some cutting,</i>

06:41.526 --> 06:42.569
<i>and that's basically</i>
<i>what those blades</i>

06:42.569 --> 06:44.112
<i>were designed for.</i>

06:44.112 --> 06:46.197
<i>The welds look solid.</i>

06:46.197 --> 06:47.908
<i>Everything looking like it's</i>
<i>coming together pretty good.</i>

06:47.908 --> 06:50.243
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:50.243 --> 06:52.495
<i>‐ I need to take</i>
<i>the three biggest pieces,</i>

06:52.495 --> 06:55.498
<i>forge weld them together</i>
<i>into the main billet.</i>

06:55.498 --> 06:57.917
<i>I'm gonna make</i>
<i>a double‐edged dagger,</i>

06:57.917 --> 07:01.921
<i>so I have a straight point</i>
<i>with two cutting edges.</i>

07:01.921 --> 07:03.757
[bleep].

07:03.757 --> 07:04.841
I have a little gap.

07:04.841 --> 07:06.426
I'm having to go back
and re‐forge.

07:06.426 --> 07:09.137
‐ I did not see Rocky
when he layered them.

07:09.137 --> 07:11.973
Clean in between‐‐you've got
forge scale in there,

07:11.973 --> 07:13.725
so you got forge scale
in between,

07:13.725 --> 07:15.393
it's not gonna take.

07:15.393 --> 07:17.520
<i>‐ I'm forging all</i>
<i>these three pieces here,</i>

07:17.520 --> 07:19.522
<i>alternating between</i>
<i>the Big Blue,</i>

07:19.522 --> 07:22.275
<i>the press,</i>
<i>and my eight‐pound hammer.</i>

07:22.275 --> 07:24.110
<i>That little weld</i>
<i>is starting to set,</i>

07:24.110 --> 07:25.654
and they're coming together.

07:25.654 --> 07:28.948
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:28.948 --> 07:31.576
‐ I have to start
shaping my blade.

07:31.576 --> 07:33.203
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:33.203 --> 07:36.956
‐ Chris has actually got a nice
blade shape going for him.

07:36.956 --> 07:40.669
<i>‐ I'm planning to make</i>
<i>a hunter‐style knife</i>

07:40.669 --> 07:43.963
<i>that I normally do at home.</i>

07:43.963 --> 07:45.131
[bleep].

07:45.131 --> 07:46.758
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:46.758 --> 07:48.301
<i>But I do see some spots</i>

07:48.301 --> 07:52.514
that are can basically
separating from my billet.

07:52.514 --> 07:55.392
<i>But I plan to make this end</i>
<i>part of my handle,</i>

07:55.392 --> 07:59.771
and hopefully the other side
will be nice and welded solid.

07:59.771 --> 08:01.064
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:01.064 --> 08:02.023
[groans]

08:02.023 --> 08:03.608
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:03.608 --> 08:06.152
<i>‐ I'm shaping this</i>
<i>by forging the tip first</i>

08:06.152 --> 08:07.320
and go from there.

08:07.320 --> 08:08.905
Very nice!

08:08.905 --> 08:10.657
<i>As I'm shaping this,</i>
<i>it's turning out</i>

08:10.657 --> 08:12.200
<i>to not really be a bowie,</i>

08:12.200 --> 08:14.828
so I go for more
of a kukri‐style blade.

08:14.828 --> 08:16.830
<i>‐ Zane's shape is interesting.</i>

08:16.830 --> 08:20.333
It's kind of that almost kukri,
almost yataghan shape,

08:20.333 --> 08:21.751
which is great for slicing

08:21.751 --> 08:23.378
but not so great
for stabbing.

08:23.378 --> 08:25.004
‐ To be able
to stab with that,

08:25.004 --> 08:27.841
it's up to the end user
to adjust a little bit

08:27.841 --> 08:30.260
to make the angle
be one for penetrating

08:30.260 --> 08:31.219
when you're thrusting.

08:31.219 --> 08:34.180
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:34.180 --> 08:37.183
‐ I take the two
smaller size springs,

08:37.183 --> 08:38.518
<i>heat them all up,</i>

08:38.518 --> 08:40.687
<i>wrap the small one</i>
<i>around the medium.</i>

08:40.687 --> 08:42.856
‐ Rocky's doing this
the hardest way

08:42.856 --> 08:44.733
that it can be done, yes?

08:44.733 --> 08:47.694
‐ Him and Tyler are
in a horse race on that one.

08:47.694 --> 08:50.030
<i>‐ So now I need to wrap</i>
<i>my little springs</i>

08:50.030 --> 08:52.866
around the main billet and
get it forge welded together.

08:52.866 --> 08:54.743
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:54.743 --> 08:57.370
<i>If I don't get all these</i>
<i>little springs</i>

08:57.370 --> 08:59.164
to wrap around the big one
and forge weld together,

08:59.164 --> 09:01.124
then I don't meet
my parameters.

09:01.124 --> 09:02.584
‐ Here we go.

09:02.584 --> 09:03.960
‐ Oh, this is gonna be nice.
Here we go.

09:03.960 --> 09:06.546
He's got a snakelike coil

09:06.546 --> 09:08.715
like a hot boa constrictor.

09:08.715 --> 09:09.841
‐ And you can see it moving.

09:09.841 --> 09:11.426
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:11.426 --> 09:14.220
‐ So I take it over
to the press...

09:14.220 --> 09:16.473
and the ends start
to duckbill on me.

09:16.473 --> 09:18.850
[bleep].

09:18.850 --> 09:21.269
all: Oh, oh, oh!

09:21.269 --> 09:23.063
<i>‐ I only have two options:</i>

09:23.063 --> 09:25.065
<i>either start over again</i>

09:25.065 --> 09:27.400
<i>or push through it</i>
<i>and make this thing work.</i>

09:27.400 --> 09:28.651
‐ Bladesmiths!

09:28.651 --> 09:31.571
You have just 60 minutes
remaining!

09:31.571 --> 09:32.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:32.572 --> 09:34.282
‐ If this weld doesn't stick,

09:34.282 --> 09:36.868
I'm gonna have
a very tough time

09:36.868 --> 09:38.411
<i>having enough to finish</i>

09:38.411 --> 09:40.747
<i>what I need to do</i>
<i>with the rest of it.</i>

09:40.747 --> 09:43.500
‐ When Tyler went to do
that last weld of his,

09:43.500 --> 09:45.919
the first time he did it,
the weld sheared.

09:45.919 --> 09:47.504
It kind of slid to the side.

09:47.504 --> 09:50.590
He had to reheat, reflux,
go back to the press.

09:50.590 --> 09:53.593
So I'm hoping
that weld is there.

09:53.593 --> 09:55.345
all: Oh!

09:55.345 --> 09:55.386
‐ [bleep].

09:57.806 --> 09:59.349
It's already past the point
where I'm gonna be able

09:59.349 --> 10:01.434
to get it back in the forge
and flux it and fix it.

10:01.434 --> 10:03.978
I can just pull
the old spring off

10:03.978 --> 10:06.189
<i>and clean everything up</i>
<i>and start over.</i>

10:06.189 --> 10:08.691
‐ In the first 20 minutes
of this competition,

10:08.691 --> 10:12.112
if Tyler had thought to drop
one little piece

10:12.112 --> 10:14.948
of a third size spring
into his can,

10:14.948 --> 10:17.283
he wouldn't have been going
through all this trouble.

10:17.283 --> 10:19.285
<i>‐ First I've gotta</i>
<i>get the canister clean</i>

10:19.285 --> 10:21.162
<i>and get a new piece of steel</i>
<i>in the forge</i>

10:21.162 --> 10:23.498
so that I can start sizing
it up to fit the canister.

10:23.498 --> 10:26.459
<i>[rock music]</i>

10:26.459 --> 10:28.169
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:28.169 --> 10:30.588
<i>‐ I got all the welds</i>
<i>starting to set.</i>

10:30.588 --> 10:32.841
It's almost one
homogenous piece of steel.

10:32.841 --> 10:36.136
<i>Now I gotta turn this thing</i>
<i>into a knife.</i>

10:36.136 --> 10:37.637
‐ Rocky just quenched.

10:37.637 --> 10:40.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:40.640 --> 10:42.142
<i>‐ It's good and straight.</i>

10:42.142 --> 10:44.185
The edge
should be really hard.

10:44.185 --> 10:47.647
<i>Go back to the grinder</i>
<i>and get this thing cleaned up.</i>

10:47.647 --> 10:50.525
It's up to the judges now.

10:50.525 --> 10:52.986
<i>‐ I got the basic shape</i>
<i>to my blade,</i>

10:52.986 --> 10:57.490
and I decided to grind away
as much of this mild steel can

10:57.490 --> 11:00.076
to reveal the pattern
underneath.

11:00.076 --> 11:02.871
<i>I have 15 minutes left</i>
<i>on the clock.</i>

11:02.871 --> 11:04.330
I'm ready to quench.

11:04.330 --> 11:07.208
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:07.208 --> 11:09.335
<i>It's...fairly straight.</i>

11:09.335 --> 11:11.004
I think it's okay.

11:11.004 --> 11:12.547
<i>‐ So I get my blade</i>
<i>nice and hot,</i>

11:12.547 --> 11:15.592
<i>and now it is ready</i>
<i>to be dunked in the oil.</i>

11:15.592 --> 11:17.343
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:17.343 --> 11:19.470
‐ Doug,
how does Zane's blade look?

11:19.470 --> 11:21.681
‐ It's refined.

11:21.681 --> 11:23.600
Looks pretty good.
<i>‐ My edge is hard.</i>

11:23.600 --> 11:25.226
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>about the rest of my blade,</i>

11:25.226 --> 11:27.520
but hopefully that's all
it'll take for me to pass.

11:27.520 --> 11:29.147
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:29.147 --> 11:30.273
‐ Five minutes!

11:30.273 --> 11:31.399
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:31.399 --> 11:32.734
<i>‐ I finish my second attempt</i>

11:32.734 --> 11:35.361
to forge weld
this billet together.

11:35.361 --> 11:38.198
<i>It's got some what looks</i>
<i>like delaminations</i>

11:38.198 --> 11:40.033
going down the center
of the blade.

11:40.033 --> 11:43.244
‐ We don't want to just see
a beat‐up brick of steel.

11:43.244 --> 11:44.329
‐ Right.

11:44.329 --> 11:46.539
Tyler needs
to quench that blade

11:46.539 --> 11:48.875
and finish his grinding
and etch it.

11:48.875 --> 11:51.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:51.544 --> 11:52.879
‐ Tyler just quenched.
‐ There you go, done.

11:52.879 --> 11:56.216
‐ I pull it out.
It's hard. It's straight.

11:56.216 --> 11:57.717
<i>Get to the grinder</i>
<i>and clean it up a little bit</i>

11:57.717 --> 11:59.969
<i>so I can get it in the acid.</i>

11:59.969 --> 12:01.888
‐ Five, four,

12:01.888 --> 12:05.058
three, two, one!

12:05.058 --> 12:06.351
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

12:06.351 --> 12:07.435
Drop your tools.

12:07.435 --> 12:10.563
This first round of competition
is over!

12:10.563 --> 12:11.564
‐ Whoo!

12:11.564 --> 12:12.899
[applause]

12:12.899 --> 12:13.942
Well done.

12:13.942 --> 12:15.735
‐ Congrats, man.

12:15.735 --> 12:18.655
‐ Looking at my original design
and what I've got now,

12:18.655 --> 12:20.949
<i>I'm not feeling great.</i>

12:20.949 --> 12:23.409
I am extremely worried
about the delamination,

12:23.409 --> 12:26.704
<i>'cause that can cause</i>
<i>a catastrophic failure.</i>

12:26.704 --> 12:29.415
‐ Bladesmiths, in this
first round of competition,

12:29.415 --> 12:30.750
we asked each of you to take

12:30.750 --> 12:33.628
three different size
5160 springs

12:33.628 --> 12:37.006
and forge them into a signature
blade in your signature style.

12:37.006 --> 12:40.551
Now, each of your blades
has fulfilled those parameters.

12:40.551 --> 12:41.594
However, only three of you

12:41.594 --> 12:43.263
can move forward
in this competition.

12:43.263 --> 12:44.555
Zane.

12:44.555 --> 12:46.099
<i>[tense percussive music]</i>

12:46.099 --> 12:48.309
<i>You have an absolutely</i>
<i>beautiful blade here.</i>

12:48.309 --> 12:49.936
<i>The steel is beautiful.</i>

12:49.936 --> 12:50.937
You may collect your blade.

12:50.937 --> 12:52.939
You're moving on
in this competition.

12:52.939 --> 12:55.024
‐ I'm really happy
to be in round two.

12:55.024 --> 12:56.484
<i>I'm young, I'm definitely</i>
<i>less experienced</i>

12:56.484 --> 12:58.444
<i>than these other smiths,</i>
<i>and I genuinely</i>

12:58.444 --> 13:00.321
did not think
that I would make it this far.

13:00.321 --> 13:01.781
‐ Chris.

13:01.781 --> 13:02.949
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:02.949 --> 13:04.158
<i>It ain't perfect.</i>

13:04.158 --> 13:05.827
There's some problems,
but collect your steel.

13:05.827 --> 13:07.287
You're moving on.

13:07.287 --> 13:10.123
‐ I'm safe, and it was like
a ton of bricks

13:10.123 --> 13:11.958
<i>just lifting off my chest.</i>

13:11.958 --> 13:13.042
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:13.042 --> 13:14.294
‐ Rocky.

13:14.294 --> 13:15.753
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:15.753 --> 13:17.880
There's some serious issues
with your blade here.

13:17.880 --> 13:21.467
<i>Your tang has separations</i>
<i>in your layers.</i>

13:21.467 --> 13:24.345
It's not fully welded.
The shape is very rough.

13:24.345 --> 13:26.014
You're gonna have to do
a lot of work in this round

13:26.014 --> 13:27.307
to catch up.

13:27.307 --> 13:29.851
Come and collect your blade.
You're moving on.

13:29.851 --> 13:31.853
<i>‐ I'm proud of myself,</i>
<i>not so much of the blade.</i>

13:31.853 --> 13:33.313
<i>I've done better work.</i>

13:33.313 --> 13:34.689
<i>My knife has some issues,</i>
<i>but I believe</i>

13:34.689 --> 13:37.608
it's gonna work out
really good in the testing.

13:37.608 --> 13:39.152
‐ Tyler.

13:39.152 --> 13:40.486
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:40.486 --> 13:42.780
<i>Your blade is</i>
<i>the least finished out here.</i>

13:42.780 --> 13:44.657
The tang is very rough.

13:44.657 --> 13:47.160
<i>You have a seam running down</i>
<i>the center of your blade.</i>

13:47.160 --> 13:49.495
And the judges just feel that
you won't be able to finish

13:49.495 --> 13:51.456
with the time that's given
in the second round.

13:51.456 --> 13:54.459
For that reason, I have to ask
you to please leave The Forge.

13:54.459 --> 13:57.378
<i>[dramatic rock music]</i>

13:57.378 --> 13:59.589
‐ I'm not super surprised.

13:59.589 --> 14:02.675
<i>I knew I had that big</i>
<i>delamination down the sides.</i>

14:02.675 --> 14:04.594
If I had to do it again,
I would've put everything

14:04.594 --> 14:06.846
<i>in one canister</i>
<i>and just gone from there</i>

14:06.846 --> 14:08.181
<i>and it would've been solid.</i>

14:08.181 --> 14:10.558
<i>I still have a lot to learn,</i>

14:10.558 --> 14:13.686
and I do intend to keep on
making knives every single day

14:13.686 --> 14:16.856
and just keep pushing myself
and pushing my boundaries.

14:16.856 --> 14:18.900
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:18.900 --> 14:20.860
‐ Bladesmiths, congratulations.

14:20.860 --> 14:23.279
You've made it to the second
round of this competition,

14:23.279 --> 14:24.947
and now that those blades
have been tempered,

14:24.947 --> 14:26.866
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

14:26.866 --> 14:28.242
by attaching handles to them

14:28.242 --> 14:31.412
<i>and include guards</i>
<i>and pommels, or butt caps.</i>

14:31.412 --> 14:32.872
Additionally,
by the end of this round,

14:32.872 --> 14:36.042
those blades must be
acid‐etched, sharp, and strong,

14:36.042 --> 14:38.377
because we'll be testing them
for strength and durability

14:38.377 --> 14:40.713
in a fuel can stab‐and‐chop

14:40.713 --> 14:44.884
and for edge retention in
a leather vest stab‐and‐slice.

14:44.884 --> 14:45.927
Good luck.

14:45.927 --> 14:48.221
Your two hours starts...now.

14:48.221 --> 14:50.056
<i>[rock music]</i>

14:50.056 --> 14:51.766
All right, each one
of these blades

14:51.766 --> 14:53.893
is very heavy
and has a long way to go.

14:53.893 --> 14:55.978
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:55.978 --> 14:57.396
‐ The game plan
for this round is,

14:57.396 --> 15:00.066
I'm going to finish up my blade
first and foremost.

15:00.066 --> 15:03.277
‐ Zane would have a lot better
control and better pressure

15:03.277 --> 15:05.154
if he would stand
in front of the grinder

15:05.154 --> 15:06.781
instead of off to the side.
‐ Right.

15:06.781 --> 15:08.074
<i>‐ Blade's looking pretty good.</i>

15:08.074 --> 15:10.409
<i>Right now, I have to get</i>
<i>this blade sharpened</i>

15:10.409 --> 15:11.953
<i>and into the acid.</i>

15:11.953 --> 15:13.079
<i>Then I have</i>
<i>to put a handle on it</i>

15:13.079 --> 15:15.081
with a guard and a butt cap.

15:15.081 --> 15:16.749
All right.

15:16.749 --> 15:18.251
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:18.251 --> 15:19.752
‐ My blade is beefy.

15:19.752 --> 15:21.129
It's a lot thicker
than it needs to be.

15:21.129 --> 15:23.756
‐ The way that Chris
is grinding on that wheel,

15:23.756 --> 15:25.466
he's rolling
right up to the edge,

15:25.466 --> 15:28.261
so he's gonna make that tip
very, very thin and delicate.

15:28.261 --> 15:30.596
So there's a good chance
when you stab into those drums,

15:30.596 --> 15:31.973
you're gonna lose that tip.

15:31.973 --> 15:33.599
<i>‐ Time's flying by.</i>

15:33.599 --> 15:36.144
<i>I decide it's time to stop</i>
<i>on the grinder for right now,</i>

15:36.144 --> 15:39.272
get moving on my handle.

15:39.272 --> 15:41.190
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:41.190 --> 15:43.651
‐ Rocky's got issues with his
blade and his tang especially.

15:43.651 --> 15:45.611
He's got a seam
in his tang

15:45.611 --> 15:46.946
that you can actually
see through.

15:46.946 --> 15:49.448
‐ If I don't fill this gap,
then we're in trouble.

15:49.448 --> 15:52.493
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:52.493 --> 15:55.121
‐ Rocky's putting some
welding beads on his tang

15:55.121 --> 15:56.664
where he had
that opening.

15:56.664 --> 15:59.000
‐ Just gentle taps, fill it in,

15:59.000 --> 16:00.710
and then worry
about grinding it all.

16:00.710 --> 16:03.963
<i>‐ I welded them all up and got</i>
<i>them straightened up already,</i>

16:03.963 --> 16:05.965
<i>so I'm almost ready to start</i>
<i>putting the handle on.</i>

16:05.965 --> 16:07.550
Feeling really good right now.

16:07.550 --> 16:09.302
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:09.302 --> 16:10.678
‐ My blade is in good shape.

16:10.678 --> 16:12.805
<i>Now I'm ready to start</i>
<i>working on this guard.</i>

16:12.805 --> 16:14.515
‐ Zane's just
rolling right along.

16:14.515 --> 16:16.142
He took some weight
off of that blade,

16:16.142 --> 16:17.643
and it's looking really nice.

16:17.643 --> 16:20.646
<i>‐ I grabbed some scrap tubing</i>
<i>from the scrap pile.</i>

16:20.646 --> 16:22.857
<i>By using this tube,</i>
<i>I can hit the top of it</i>

16:22.857 --> 16:26.319
and it'll force that guard down
to the shoulders of the blade

16:26.319 --> 16:28.112
without deforming it too badly.

16:28.112 --> 16:31.824
‐ My concern is
the size of Zane's guard,

16:31.824 --> 16:33.826
and a small guard doesn't
really keep your hand

16:33.826 --> 16:35.161
from moving forward that much.

16:35.161 --> 16:36.621
‐ Right.

16:36.621 --> 16:38.164
‐ Bladesmiths!

16:38.164 --> 16:39.999
One hour has elapsed!

16:39.999 --> 16:41.834
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:41.834 --> 16:45.004
<i>‐ I got all my pieces ready,</i>
<i>and I have to assemble it</i>

16:45.004 --> 16:46.380
<i>and epoxy everything together.</i>

16:46.380 --> 16:48.299
I also wanna compression fit it

16:48.299 --> 16:50.676
by mushrooming the end
of my tang over the butt cap.

16:50.676 --> 16:53.012
‐ He's just cold hammering
that thing right now.

16:53.012 --> 16:55.514
‐ I'd rather see
the softened tang peened over

16:55.514 --> 16:57.058
as opposed
to throwing heat on it,

16:57.058 --> 16:59.352
'cause then all you're gonna do
is cook your epoxy.

16:59.352 --> 17:01.187
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:01.187 --> 17:02.939
‐ Ah, that ain't gonna work.

17:02.939 --> 17:04.690
<i>I'm wasting precious time.</i>

17:04.690 --> 17:07.276
‐ Rocky just found
the oxyacetylene torch,

17:07.276 --> 17:10.029
so all those things you
just said, J., are coming true.

17:10.029 --> 17:12.114
<i>‐ I don't wanna add heat</i>
<i>to the tang,</i>

17:12.114 --> 17:14.533
but I have to do something,
'cause that's not moving.

17:14.533 --> 17:15.952
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:15.952 --> 17:18.871
<i>‐ I'm fairly happy</i>
<i>with the fit of the handle.</i>

17:18.871 --> 17:22.708
Now I'm gonna use my hammer to
peen over the end of the tang.

17:22.708 --> 17:24.752
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:24.752 --> 17:27.755
And it just doesn't seem like
it wants to budge.

17:27.755 --> 17:29.924
Ugh, no, no, no, no!

17:29.924 --> 17:32.760
I decided I'm gonna go
for the oxyacetylene setup.

17:32.760 --> 17:34.053
‐ Oh, no, here we go.
‐ [groans]

17:34.053 --> 17:36.597
‐ So Chris has moved over
to the oxyacetylene torch.

17:36.597 --> 17:38.474
‐ I think it's a monkey see,
monkey do kind of thing,

17:38.474 --> 17:39.600
what you got going on
right now.

17:41.394 --> 17:42.645
<i>[rock music]</i>

17:42.645 --> 17:45.856
‐ We've got Rocky
in this corner

17:45.856 --> 17:47.650
and Chris
in the opposite corner.

17:47.650 --> 17:49.068
Who will come out on top?

17:49.068 --> 17:51.112
<i>‐ I'm worried</i>
<i>about heating the tang,</i>

17:51.112 --> 17:53.239
<i>'cause that's gonna make</i>
<i>the epoxy melt.</i>

17:53.239 --> 17:55.449
But I have no choice.

17:55.449 --> 17:58.286
‐ Rocky's heading to the post
vise in the back of The Forge.

17:58.286 --> 18:01.455
It looks like he's gonna try
to peen everything down.

18:01.455 --> 18:04.250
‐ I started hitting with the
hammer and mushroomed it out.

18:04.250 --> 18:06.085
<i>Hopefully the epoxy stays set.</i>

18:06.085 --> 18:08.754
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

18:08.754 --> 18:10.214
<i>‐ What I'm hoping</i>
<i>to do with this</i>

18:10.214 --> 18:12.800
is soften that metal up
a little bit more

18:12.800 --> 18:15.094
to make it easier
to spread that material,

18:15.094 --> 18:17.138
but it's just not working out
for me right now.

18:17.138 --> 18:19.932
I decide
to go back to the vise

18:19.932 --> 18:22.268
and I'm going to town
on this thing.

18:22.268 --> 18:24.937
[hammer banging sharply]

18:24.937 --> 18:27.398
‐ Chris is whaling
on that thing, man.

18:27.398 --> 18:29.358
‐ Does not have to do
that much swinging

18:29.358 --> 18:31.027
to peen it over.

18:31.027 --> 18:32.486
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:32.486 --> 18:33.988
<i>‐ It finally starts to move,</i>

18:33.988 --> 18:35.990
but if this knife
is gonna break,

18:35.990 --> 18:38.284
it's gonna break right now
while I'm doing this.

18:38.284 --> 18:39.452
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:39.452 --> 18:41.454
‐ Well, hey, man,
there's no doubt in my mind

18:41.454 --> 18:43.706
that Chris' handle is sturdy.

18:43.706 --> 18:44.874
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:44.874 --> 18:46.292
Five minutes!

18:46.292 --> 18:48.127
<i>[rock music]</i>

18:48.127 --> 18:49.337
‐ I've got everything glued up.

18:49.337 --> 18:51.047
<i>I begin cutting out</i>
<i>the rough shape</i>

18:51.047 --> 18:52.840
<i>of what I want my handle</i>
<i>to look like.</i>

18:52.840 --> 18:55.509
‐ Now, the thing Zane's
gotta worry about now

18:55.509 --> 18:58.971
is not cutting too far in
and going into the channel.

18:58.971 --> 19:02.350
<i>‐ The shaping is going</i>
<i>exactly how I wanted it to go.</i>

19:02.350 --> 19:05.144
I'm very, very pleased with it.

19:05.144 --> 19:06.479
Ooh.

19:06.479 --> 19:09.148
I see this massive gaping hole
in my finger troil

19:09.148 --> 19:10.983
where I have ground through

19:10.983 --> 19:13.402
to the void where my tang
is hidden.

19:13.402 --> 19:14.987
‐ I knew it. I knew it.

19:14.987 --> 19:17.198
<i>‐ Well, can't do anything now.</i>

19:17.198 --> 19:19.825
Here you go!
[laughs]

19:19.825 --> 19:21.827
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:21.827 --> 19:23.996
<i>‐ I'm trying to shape</i>
<i>the handle, the pommel,</i>

19:23.996 --> 19:25.498
the crossguard
all at once.

19:25.498 --> 19:27.958
<i>Normally I like</i>
<i>to take my time on handles.</i>

19:27.958 --> 19:30.795
<i>I'm looking at the clock.</i>
<i>I have minutes left.</i>

19:30.795 --> 19:33.673
‐ I'd say Chris is starting
to put an edge on his blade.

19:33.673 --> 19:35.341
<i>‐ I rush through the edge.</i>

19:35.341 --> 19:37.385
<i>I put the best one on</i>
<i>that I can,</i>

19:37.385 --> 19:39.595
and I have
a couple minutes left

19:39.595 --> 19:41.013
<i>to get an etch</i>
<i>on this knife.</i>

19:41.013 --> 19:43.224
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:43.224 --> 19:44.350
‐ Two minutes!

19:44.350 --> 19:45.851
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:45.851 --> 19:47.520
<i>‐ I like the way</i>
<i>my blade's coming together.</i>

19:47.520 --> 19:50.272
Now I need to get everything
all polished up now

19:50.272 --> 19:52.692
and then go ahead
and put my cutting edge on.

19:52.692 --> 19:55.236
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:55.236 --> 19:56.779
<i>As I'm grinding</i>
<i>my cutting edge in,</i>

19:56.779 --> 19:59.448
I feel that the butt cap
is a little bit loose.

19:59.448 --> 20:02.535
<i>If I leave it like this,</i>
<i>the butt cap could come off.</i>

20:02.535 --> 20:03.619
‐ What is he doing?

20:03.619 --> 20:04.829
‐ What he might be doing,

20:04.829 --> 20:06.372
if he's getting a little bit
of movement,

20:06.372 --> 20:07.873
by driving a chisel in,

20:07.873 --> 20:09.750
he will split the tang
a little bit,

20:09.750 --> 20:11.252
push it to either side,

20:11.252 --> 20:12.878
which could
lock things together nicely.

20:12.878 --> 20:15.381
<i>‐ I give it a few strikes</i>
<i>and I check it</i>

20:15.381 --> 20:17.717
and I test it and then I don't
believe it's going anywhere.

20:17.717 --> 20:19.802
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:19.802 --> 20:21.721
‐ Five, four,

20:21.721 --> 20:24.557
three, two, one!

20:24.557 --> 20:26.142
Bladesmiths,
stop what you're doing.

20:26.142 --> 20:28.978
This second round
of competition is over.

20:28.978 --> 20:30.146
‐ Good job.
‐ Whoo!

20:30.146 --> 20:31.897
‐ [laughs]
‐ That was a party.

20:31.897 --> 20:32.940
[laughter]

20:32.940 --> 20:34.442
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

20:34.442 --> 20:36.068
‐ This is probably the fastest

20:36.068 --> 20:37.611
<i>I've ever</i>
<i>had to shape a handle.</i>

20:37.611 --> 20:40.406
<i>I'd say my confidence level</i>
<i>right now is fairly good.</i>

20:40.406 --> 20:42.658
<i>It held up to me</i>
<i>beating on it with a hammer.</i>

20:42.658 --> 20:43.993
I think it should be okay.

20:43.993 --> 20:45.828
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:45.828 --> 20:49.290
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to our strength test,

20:49.290 --> 20:52.460
the oil barrel stab‐and‐chop.

20:52.460 --> 20:54.295
To test the tip, edge,

20:54.295 --> 20:56.255
and overall construction
of your weapons,

20:56.255 --> 20:59.300
I'm gonna take your blades
and repeatedly

20:59.300 --> 21:02.261
and mercilessly chop and beat
into these oil drums.

21:02.261 --> 21:04.764
And, Chris, you're up first.
How you feeling?

21:04.764 --> 21:05.806
‐ Okay.

21:05.806 --> 21:07.600
‐ All right, let's do it.

21:07.600 --> 21:09.602
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:09.602 --> 21:12.271
<i>‐ These oil drums</i>
<i>are pretty intimidating.</i>

21:12.271 --> 21:15.024
<i>I really hope that I have</i>

21:15.024 --> 21:16.776
a strong enough point
on my blade

21:16.776 --> 21:20.696
and also a strong enough edge.

21:20.696 --> 21:27.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:28.788 --> 21:32.625
‐ [grunting]

21:32.625 --> 21:34.126
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:34.126 --> 21:35.294
We're not done yet.

21:35.294 --> 21:36.337
[laughter]

21:36.337 --> 21:40.299
‐ [grunting]

21:40.299 --> 21:45.971
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:45.971 --> 21:48.307
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

21:48.307 --> 21:49.642
All right, Chris.

21:49.642 --> 21:50.851
Everything's tight.

21:50.851 --> 21:53.771
You lost the slightest bit
of your tip,

21:53.771 --> 21:55.189
and on your edge,

21:55.189 --> 21:57.316
the only thing that's missing
is the etch.

21:57.316 --> 21:59.527
Very good job.
‐ Thank you.

21:59.527 --> 22:01.987
‐ Okay, Zane, after seeing
that, how do you feel?

22:01.987 --> 22:03.197
‐ Little bit nervous

22:03.197 --> 22:04.740
but excited
to see what happens.

22:04.740 --> 22:07.326
‐ So am I.
[laughter]

22:07.326 --> 22:08.744
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:08.744 --> 22:09.829
<i>‐ Chris has already gone.</i>

22:09.829 --> 22:11.997
<i>Overall,</i>
<i>his weapon worked well.</i>

22:11.997 --> 22:13.457
<i>I'm nervous.</i>

22:13.457 --> 22:15.042
<i>I don't think that my blade</i>
<i>has hardened fully,</i>

22:15.042 --> 22:18.170
<i>and my mind is just</i>
<i>a bee's nest of emotions</i>

22:18.170 --> 22:20.923
and thoughts and fears.
[laughs]

22:20.923 --> 22:24.510
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:24.510 --> 22:25.511
<i>[rock music]</i>

22:25.511 --> 22:29.181
‐ [grunting]

22:29.181 --> 22:35.855
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:35.855 --> 22:38.858
[grunting]

22:38.858 --> 22:42.403
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:42.403 --> 22:45.739
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

22:45.739 --> 22:47.074
Good job, Zane.

22:47.074 --> 22:49.243
For the batoning,
it was difficult

22:49.243 --> 22:51.871
because you've got
a drop here.

22:51.871 --> 22:54.623
So a couple times,
I'd hit and glance.

22:54.623 --> 22:58.377
But when it went through, it
punctured down a good distance.

22:58.377 --> 23:00.379
This is one of the reasons
I'm wearing a glove,

23:00.379 --> 23:01.881
blowing through that pocket.

23:01.881 --> 23:03.048
'Cause this will
tear your finger up.

23:03.048 --> 23:04.967
But your tip and edge
held up fine.

23:04.967 --> 23:05.926
Good job.

23:05.926 --> 23:07.303
‐ Thank you, Judge.

23:07.303 --> 23:09.221
‐ Rocky, how you feeling?

23:09.221 --> 23:10.556
‐ Nervous.

23:10.556 --> 23:12.224
‐ It's all right.
I'll be calm for both of us.

23:12.224 --> 23:13.726
[laughter]

23:13.726 --> 23:15.394
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:15.394 --> 23:18.063
<i>‐ I watched</i>
<i>the other two guys' blades</i>

23:18.063 --> 23:19.940
<i>perform very well.</i>

23:19.940 --> 23:22.151
<i>Little nervous how</i>
<i>my blade's gonna hold up.</i>

23:22.151 --> 23:24.194
I'm worried about the
construction on that pommel.

23:26.155 --> 23:27.781
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

23:27.781 --> 23:29.992
‐ Little nervous about
how my blade's gonna hold up

23:29.992 --> 23:32.703
but very confident
it's gonna work out.

23:32.703 --> 23:35.164
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:35.164 --> 23:36.916
‐ [grunting]

23:36.916 --> 23:40.127
<i>[rock music]</i>

23:40.127 --> 23:42.796
[grunting]

23:42.796 --> 23:49.094
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:54.433 --> 23:57.061
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

23:57.061 --> 23:59.396
Rocky, your tip held up fine

23:59.396 --> 24:01.357
and your edge held up fine.

24:01.357 --> 24:04.610
The handle,
little on the square side.

24:04.610 --> 24:08.739
And your pommel separated.
That's a bit of an issue.

24:08.739 --> 24:11.283
But overall,
your blade survived.

24:11.283 --> 24:12.326
Good job.

24:12.326 --> 24:14.119
‐ Thank you.

24:14.119 --> 24:17.206
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:17.206 --> 24:18.499
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

24:18.499 --> 24:20.334
To find out
how sharp your edges are,

24:20.334 --> 24:24.171
the leather vest
stab‐and‐slice.

24:24.171 --> 24:26.006
Chris, you're up first.
You ready for this?

24:26.006 --> 24:27.800
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Let's do this.

24:27.800 --> 24:30.302
<i>[rock music]</i>

24:30.302 --> 24:37.309
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:46.735 --> 24:49.196
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

24:49.196 --> 24:51.657
All right, Chris, let's talk
about your blade here.

24:51.657 --> 24:53.993
It's not very sharp.

24:53.993 --> 24:57.121
When you're slashing, the sheer
weight of your blade here

24:57.121 --> 25:01.041
does cut it
but doesn't lacerate it nicely.

25:01.041 --> 25:03.585
But overall, sir,
for this test...

25:03.585 --> 25:04.670
it will cut.

25:04.670 --> 25:06.005
‐ Thank you, sir.

25:06.005 --> 25:07.464
‐ Right, Zane.
You're up.

25:07.464 --> 25:09.091
You ready?
‐ Yes, sir!

25:09.091 --> 25:10.050
‐ Let's do this.

25:10.050 --> 25:17.099
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:18.517 --> 25:21.520
<i>[rock music]</i>

25:21.520 --> 25:28.527
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:29.903 --> 25:31.071
Oop.

25:31.071 --> 25:32.114
[laughter]

25:32.114 --> 25:33.365
‐ Ouch.

25:33.365 --> 25:35.034
‐ Whoo!
[chuckles]

25:36.452 --> 25:39.872
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

25:39.872 --> 25:41.749
‐ All right, Zane, let's talk
about your blade here.

25:41.749 --> 25:44.376
The grinds that you have
on this edge are sharp,

25:44.376 --> 25:46.754
so it's able
to cut the leather.

25:46.754 --> 25:49.840
Now, stabbing, your point
does penetrate deeper in

25:49.840 --> 25:51.300
all the way through there.

25:51.300 --> 25:54.094
The one issue I had here
is the guard.

25:54.094 --> 25:56.388
The angle that you have
of your curve there

25:56.388 --> 26:00.267
actually drives my hand
to go forward as opposed to

26:00.267 --> 26:02.853
holds me back from
going any deeper than that.

26:02.853 --> 26:04.146
But overall, sir,

26:04.146 --> 26:05.397
it will cut.

26:05.397 --> 26:06.899
‐ Thank you, Doug.

26:06.899 --> 26:08.901
‐ And then there was one.
[laughter]

26:08.901 --> 26:10.652
Are you ready, Rocky?
‐ I'm ready.

26:10.652 --> 26:11.904
‐ Let's do this.

26:11.904 --> 26:18.744
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:18.744 --> 26:21.747
<i>[rock music]</i>

26:21.747 --> 26:28.754
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:31.090 --> 26:34.093
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

26:34.093 --> 26:35.594
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:35.594 --> 26:38.347
All right Rocky, let's talk
about your weapon right here.

26:38.347 --> 26:41.016
Your pommel was already loose
before we started.

26:41.016 --> 26:42.601
It didn't get any worse.

26:42.601 --> 26:45.437
The edge‐‐by slashing
with the tip,

26:45.437 --> 26:47.981
it did cut on one side
of the vest cleanly.

26:47.981 --> 26:49.983
On the other side,
it just ripped it.

26:49.983 --> 26:52.277
Edges right here
are not as sharp

26:52.277 --> 26:54.238
as I would've
expected it to be.

26:54.238 --> 26:56.949
But overall, sir,
for this test,

26:56.949 --> 26:57.950
it will cut.

26:57.950 --> 27:00.661
‐ Thank you.

27:00.661 --> 27:01.912
‐ All right, bladesmiths,

27:01.912 --> 27:03.831
I've finished
my conference with the judges,

27:03.831 --> 27:05.707
and they agree that none
of your blades are perfect.

27:05.707 --> 27:07.000
Each of them has flaws.

27:07.000 --> 27:09.545
Unfortunately, Rocky,

27:09.545 --> 27:11.547
your pommel came loose
during the strength test,

27:11.547 --> 27:13.257
and let's just face it,

27:13.257 --> 27:15.300
most of your finer knives
don't have any moving parts.

27:15.300 --> 27:18.512
For that reason, I have to
ask you please leave The Forge.

27:18.512 --> 27:19.847
‐ All right.

27:19.847 --> 27:21.390
<i>So I'm feeling</i>
<i>a little disappointed,</i>

27:21.390 --> 27:23.308
but I represented myself well.

27:23.308 --> 27:24.685
‐ Thank you.

27:24.685 --> 27:26.395
‐ I learned a lot about myself,
should've been better.

27:26.395 --> 27:29.314
<i>It's amazing what this clock</i>
<i>will do to you.</i>

27:29.314 --> 27:30.774
I'm only gonna
stop bladesmithing

27:30.774 --> 27:32.609
<i>like it's getting too old</i>
<i>to pick up that hammer</i>

27:32.609 --> 27:33.819
to work with it.

27:33.819 --> 27:36.822
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:36.822 --> 27:38.740
‐ Zane, Chris,
congratulations.

27:38.740 --> 27:39.908
You boys have made it

27:39.908 --> 27:41.326
to the final round
of this competition.

27:41.326 --> 27:42.786
Now we're sending you
back to your home forges

27:42.786 --> 27:45.831
to re‐create
an iconic weapon from history.

27:45.831 --> 27:49.501
That weapon is...

27:49.501 --> 27:52.588
the Revolutionary War
sergeant's spontoon.

27:52.588 --> 27:54.631
‐ Hmm.
[chuckles]

27:54.631 --> 27:55.632
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:55.632 --> 27:57.092
<i>‐ Replacing the halberd,</i>

27:57.092 --> 27:58.927
<i>spontoons were used throughout</i>
<i>the American Revolution</i>

27:58.927 --> 28:01.597
<i>and Napoleonic Wars by</i>
<i>British and Hessian soldiers.</i>

28:01.597 --> 28:03.223
<i>Featuring</i>
<i>a leaf‐shaped spearhead,</i>

28:03.223 --> 28:05.517
<i>the blade had</i>
<i>limited cutting ability.</i>

28:05.517 --> 28:06.852
<i>However,</i>
<i>it excelled at thrusting</i>

28:06.852 --> 28:09.104
<i>into charging</i>
<i>infantry and cavalry.</i>

28:09.104 --> 28:11.023
<i>A crossbar is attached to</i>
<i>the bottom of the spearhead</i>

28:11.023 --> 28:13.650
<i>so the blade wouldn't get</i>
<i>stuck into its target.</i>

28:13.650 --> 28:15.569
<i>Although the weapon</i>
<i>was a brutal killer,</i>

28:15.569 --> 28:17.863
<i>it was primarily used</i>
<i>as a signaling tool</i>

28:17.863 --> 28:20.407
<i>to direct orders to troops,</i>
<i>as its length was easy to spot</i>

28:20.407 --> 28:21.950
<i>across the field.</i>

28:21.950 --> 28:23.702
<i>Eventually,</i>
<i>the weapon transitioned</i>

28:23.702 --> 28:26.747
<i>to being purely an identifier</i>
<i>of rank amongst the troops.</i>

28:26.747 --> 28:29.708
<i>However, its legacy lives on</i>
<i>through popular culture,</i>

28:29.708 --> 28:31.585
<i>and you can see</i>
<i>British sergeants wield it</i>

28:31.585 --> 28:34.004
<i>in the film "Revolution."</i>

28:34.004 --> 28:37.299
Your blades must fall within
the following parameters:

28:37.299 --> 28:38.759
the length of this weapon

28:38.759 --> 28:41.386
must be no more
than 72 inches in length.

28:41.386 --> 28:44.473
The cutting edges should
measure between 8 and 9 inches.

28:44.473 --> 28:47.434
And your socket must be
at least 5 inches long.

28:47.434 --> 28:50.270
‐ I have never really
made anything

28:50.270 --> 28:52.147
like a spontoon before.

28:52.147 --> 28:56.234
I've worked on some spears
but nothing like this.

28:56.234 --> 28:57.736
‐ You'll have four days
at your home forges

28:57.736 --> 28:59.196
in which to complete
this weapon,

28:59.196 --> 29:00.447
and at the end
of those four days,

29:00.447 --> 29:02.074
you'll return
and present your weapons

29:02.074 --> 29:03.742
to our panel of expert judges,

29:03.742 --> 29:05.702
and after they've tested
the hell out of them,

29:05.702 --> 29:07.996
they'll declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

29:07.996 --> 29:12.626
who walks out of this forge
with a check for $10,000.

29:12.626 --> 29:14.628
Good luck.
We'll see you in four days.

29:14.628 --> 29:16.838
‐ All right.

29:16.838 --> 29:19.216
<i>[country rock music]</i>

29:19.216 --> 29:20.550
<i>‐ We're back in Waxhaw,</i>

29:20.550 --> 29:22.594
<i>and I have to make</i>
<i>a sergeant's spontoon.</i>

29:22.594 --> 29:23.637
[forge roaring]

29:23.637 --> 29:25.597
Here we go.
Phew!

29:25.597 --> 29:27.683
I decided to use 5160
for the blade steel

29:27.683 --> 29:29.726
<i>because it is relatively easy</i>
<i>to heat treat</i>

29:29.726 --> 29:32.938
<i>but also holds up very well</i>
<i>when under duress.</i>

29:32.938 --> 29:35.023
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:35.023 --> 29:37.526
<i>My main goal is to elongate</i>
<i>this piece of steel</i>

29:37.526 --> 29:39.152
<i>that will eventually</i>
<i>become the blade</i>

29:39.152 --> 29:40.946
so that it meets
the requirements.

29:40.946 --> 29:43.782
Yeah, it's a slow press,
but it's okay.

29:43.782 --> 29:46.034
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:46.034 --> 29:47.828
<i>‐ I'm back in my home forge.</i>

29:47.828 --> 29:49.621
I'm ready to get started.
I'm excited.

29:49.621 --> 29:51.164
[forge roaring]

29:51.164 --> 29:53.000
<i>I'm gonna build</i>
<i>a Damascus billet.</i>

29:53.000 --> 29:55.002
<i>I'm gonna try to get</i>
<i>as many layers as I can.</i>

29:55.002 --> 29:56.837
<i>I think it'll</i>
<i>impress the judges</i>

29:56.837 --> 29:59.548
and hopefully hold up
really well in the tests.

29:59.548 --> 30:01.675
<i>I got my</i>
<i>main billet cleaned up.</i>

30:01.675 --> 30:02.968
I'm gonna cut it
and restack it,

30:02.968 --> 30:04.177
<i>get it to the size I need,</i>

30:04.177 --> 30:05.303
and then I can hopefully

30:05.303 --> 30:07.472
start getting
the point shaped out.

30:07.472 --> 30:09.141
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:09.141 --> 30:10.726
Day two.

30:10.726 --> 30:12.144
<i>I'm going to be working</i>
<i>on the socket,</i>

30:12.144 --> 30:13.562
getting that more fit
and finished.

30:13.562 --> 30:14.813
<i>I'm also going to grind</i>

30:14.813 --> 30:16.648
<i>and hopefully</i>
<i>heat treat my blade.</i>

30:16.648 --> 30:19.359
For the heat treat, I'm gonna
be using this oven right here.

30:19.359 --> 30:22.487
<i>It works really well</i>
<i>with temperature control.</i>

30:22.487 --> 30:25.323
<i>I can keep my blade exactly</i>
<i>the temperature I want it</i>

30:25.323 --> 30:27.034
for how long I want it.

30:27.034 --> 30:30.162
I am nervous that my heat treat
is not gonna go well.

30:30.162 --> 30:33.373
<i>I could have the blade snap.</i>
<i>I could have it warp.</i>

30:33.373 --> 30:35.834
I could have it
just not harden at all.

30:35.834 --> 30:38.211
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:38.211 --> 30:40.505
I don't hear any tinking
sounds, so that's good.

30:40.505 --> 30:43.050
<i>Tinks are usually cracks.</i>

30:43.050 --> 30:45.927
And it's hard,
and I am so excited.

30:45.927 --> 30:48.430
Whoo!

30:48.430 --> 30:49.848
[with high‐pitched voice]
That was scary!

30:49.848 --> 30:51.099
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:51.099 --> 30:53.101
<i>‐ Yesterday</i>
<i>I got the crossguard</i>

30:53.101 --> 30:55.437
<i>and the spear to shape.</i>

30:55.437 --> 30:57.856
<i>The crossguard</i>
<i>being a separate piece</i>

30:57.856 --> 30:59.816
<i>is a concern of mine.</i>

30:59.816 --> 31:01.526
I am gonna have
to forge weld that

31:01.526 --> 31:03.820
<i>for structural integrity</i>
<i>reasons.</i>

31:03.820 --> 31:07.032
<i>Probably gonna get into some</i>
<i>welding with the MIG welder</i>

31:07.032 --> 31:08.366
just to reinforce everything.

31:08.366 --> 31:11.286
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:12.579 --> 31:13.663
It quit working.

31:13.663 --> 31:15.457
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:15.457 --> 31:17.584
This welder's really messing
with my time right now.

31:17.584 --> 31:20.212
I need to get to my heat treat.

31:20.212 --> 31:23.006
I can't do that until
I get this welded on.

31:25.884 --> 31:28.011
Not sur <i>[rock music]</i>

31:28.011 --> 31:29.930
I think my tension might've
been a little too tight.

31:29.930 --> 31:31.515
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:31.515 --> 31:32.557
That's it.

31:32.557 --> 31:34.142
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:34.142 --> 31:36.061
I figure out kind of
what was going on.

31:36.061 --> 31:38.772
Okay, it's tack welded.

31:38.772 --> 31:40.941
<i>I decided to forge weld</i>
<i>the crossguard on,</i>

31:40.941 --> 31:43.735
<i>just give it a lot more</i>
<i>structural integrity.</i>

31:43.735 --> 31:46.279
It's more like one piece
instead of two pieces.

31:46.279 --> 31:49.074
I have the crossguard
forge welded.

31:49.074 --> 31:52.410
<i>I'm going to be attaching</i>
<i>the socket for the spear</i>

31:52.410 --> 31:55.080
<i>and hopefully after that</i>
<i>get it ready for heat treat.</i>

31:55.080 --> 31:58.291
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:58.291 --> 31:59.960
‐ Day three is here.

31:59.960 --> 32:03.004
<i>I plan on finishing up</i>
<i>my blade, and then I'm going</i>

32:03.004 --> 32:07.384
<i>to weld my tang and my guard</i>
<i>to my socket.</i>

32:07.384 --> 32:09.136
[bleep].

32:09.136 --> 32:10.428
I have a dilemma here.

32:10.428 --> 32:12.514
The overall length
of the blade in the socket

32:12.514 --> 32:15.183
is about two inches shy
of what it needs to be.

32:15.183 --> 32:17.435
I'm gonna weld a piece of pipe
on the end of it,

32:17.435 --> 32:18.854
give it the same texture,

32:18.854 --> 32:20.772
and just extend it
about two inches,

32:20.772 --> 32:22.357
and then it'll fit
the requirements

32:22.357 --> 32:24.276
and I'll have a little bit
of extra space

32:24.276 --> 32:25.443
for wood to go through.

32:25.443 --> 32:27.946
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:27.946 --> 32:30.323
I really am glad that I
double‐checked and measured

32:30.323 --> 32:32.993
<i>the length of my blade,</i>
<i>because if I hadn't,</i>

32:32.993 --> 32:34.494
then I could've just gone out

32:34.494 --> 32:36.037
without even getting
to testing.

32:36.037 --> 32:38.123
That's pretty good!

32:38.123 --> 32:40.458
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:40.458 --> 32:42.085
<i>‐ It's day four</i>
<i>of my spontoon build.</i>

32:42.085 --> 32:44.504
<i>The first thing I gotta do</i>
<i>today is get the haft cut out</i>

32:44.504 --> 32:46.756
<i>and shaped down.</i>

32:46.756 --> 32:48.091
<i>I layered the wood up.</i>

32:48.091 --> 32:51.845
Hopefully the difference
in grain structure will help

32:51.845 --> 32:54.222
<i>in strengthness</i>
<i>and flexibility.</i>

32:54.222 --> 32:57.225
I left it sort of octagonal.

32:57.225 --> 32:59.060
I think it'll give it
a little better grip.

32:59.060 --> 33:00.729
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:00.729 --> 33:02.731
<i>Now it's time to get my haft</i>

33:02.731 --> 33:05.066
attached to my
spontoon spearhead.

33:05.066 --> 33:06.860
<i>This is a hell of a build.</i>

33:06.860 --> 33:08.778
<i>I'm tired. I'm sore.</i>

33:08.778 --> 33:09.988
I think it looks awesome.

33:09.988 --> 33:12.240
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:12.240 --> 33:14.701
I cut one. I'm good.

33:14.701 --> 33:20.040
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

33:20.040 --> 33:22.292
‐ Zane, Chris, welcome back
to The Forge.

33:22.292 --> 33:24.127
You boys have had four days
at your home forges

33:24.127 --> 33:26.421
to work on your finale weapons.

33:26.421 --> 33:29.174
Zane, tell the judges about
the construction of your blade.

33:29.174 --> 33:30.800
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:30.800 --> 33:33.595
<i>‐ The blade is 5160</i>
<i>high carbon steel.</i>

33:33.595 --> 33:35.972
<i>The socket and the guard</i>
<i>are both mild steel,</i>

33:35.972 --> 33:38.600
<i>and the shaft</i>
<i>is spalted maple.</i>

33:38.600 --> 33:39.893
‐ All right, all right.

33:39.893 --> 33:42.270
Chris, tell the judges
about your blade.

33:42.270 --> 33:43.813
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:43.813 --> 33:47.859
<i>‐ The blade and the crossguard</i>
<i>are both Damascus.</i>

33:47.859 --> 33:49.486
<i>The socket is mild steel.</i>

33:49.486 --> 33:54.616
